ier()`, which is interesting. I noticed a potential concern with the lack of tests for LZ4 compression; currently, we only assert that isLZ4 is false. I could add a more comprehensive test for LZ4 while avoiding overcomplicating things. \\n\\nMaybe I’ll set up a config for CBOR with default no compression and integrate JSON with LZ4 for testing. I could also check if JacksonCborSerializer respects binding compression.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing potential issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about potential failures relating to LZ4 in Native, particularly if the lz4-java library uses unsafe or metadata as a dependency. I want to keep things simple and not include \\\"Cbor compact\\\" bytes with LZ4. There are also issues with gzip assertions; `toBinary` should only compress when the length exceeds a threshold, which I’ve set to 1 byte.\\n\\nI need to look into how serialized bytes interact with the deserialization process, especially with an ActorSystem that may warn if `akka.actor.allow-java-serialization` is off. There’s also the problem of migrating old manifests with uncompressed bytes; I wonder if JSON binding compression could create more complications.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using an actual `LegacyPayload` top-level class instead of the nonexistent `com.example`. This could help avoid class loading issues that might arise. It's important to ensure that everything is structured properly to prevent any unnecessary complications, especially with legacy codes. By implementing a proper top-level class, I could potentially streamline the loading process and ensure better compatibility, which seems essential for maintaining overall system integrity.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class transformation**\\n\\nI need to manage an old class that doesn't exist anymore. To maintain compatibility with Native and library behavior, I’ll define a `final case class LegacyPayload(name: String, revision: Int)`. Then, I can rename it to Renamed. However, the tests reference the old class, which complicates things. I'll ensure that `transformClassName` is tested properly and check that it handles migration from LegacyPayload to RenamedPayload effectively, reducing risks with ClassNotFound and enhancing configuration.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_FCn6esfYDkv8VrERs8287UVy|fc_0b70f9f7ffa7ea7e0169fb0f32c0f881959b15caf6d7a5bf82", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.typesafe.akka/akka-serialization-jackson_2.13/2.6.21/src/test/scala/com_typesafe_akka/akka_serialization_jackson_2_13/Akka_serialization_jackson_2_13Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "  def migrationTransformsLegacyJsonAndClassName(): Unit = {\n    val legacyClassName: String = \"com.example.LegacyPayload\"\n    val config: Config = configWithBindings(\n      Map(classOf[RenamedPayload] -> \"jackson-json\"),\n      s\"\"\"\n        akka.serialization.jackson.allowed-class-prefix += \"com.example.\"\n        akka.serialization.jackson.migrations {\n          \"$legacyClassName\" = \"${classOf[LegacyPayloadMigration].getName}\"\n        }\n        \"\"\"\n    )", "newText": "  def migrationTransformsLegacyJsonAndClassName(): Unit = {\n    val legacyClassName: String = classOf[LegacyPayload].getName\n    val config: Config = configWithBindings(\n      Map(classOf[RenamedPayload] -> \"jackson-json\"),\n      s\"\"\"\n        akka.serialization.jackson.migrations {\n          \"$legacyClassName\" = \"${classOf[LegacyPayloadMigration].getName}\"\n        }\n        \"\"\"\n    )"}, {"oldText": "final case class RenamedPayload(text: String, revision: Int)\n\nfinal class LegacyPayloadMigration extends JacksonMigration {", "newText": "final case class RenamedPayload(text: String, revision: Int)\n\nfinal case class LegacyPayload(name: String, revision: Int)\n\nfinal class LegacyPayloadMigration extends JacksonMigration {"}]}}], "api": "openai-respons